  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Farewell Letter for Yi Sagwan Upon His Posting to Geoje
  author: Yi Gyeongbo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I have indeed heard tell of this place called Geoje—the uttermost reach of the southern realm. There, homes nestle amid waters, surrounded on all sides by nothing but the vast and restless sea. Noxious mists rise thick as steam, and gales never cease their fury. When summer comes, mosquitoes swarm—some larger than bees themselves—descending upon men in clouds. Truly, a place to fear. Those who serve as magistrate there are mostly those cast down by demotion.

    Yet you, with talents bright and keen, have labored in the archives of the Secretariat, ever shouldering the weight of recording history for ten thousand generations. Your deeds deserve promotion's command, and yet instead you fall to this place. How can one not grieve?

    And yet there are two things worthy of celebration. When Heaven seeks to accomplish great things, it first tests with hardship—such is the way of yin and yang. That you, innocent of crime, are sent to this exile means Heaven's blessing surely draws near. This is cause for joy, the first.

    Moreover, those who attain the Way profoundly often dwell in solitude and silence. Why? Because such focus, such singularity of purpose, deepens the path's entry. Where you are going, the land is quiet and people few. Your office is light, your duties simple. No worldly concern can disturb your peace. Sitting in stillness within emptiness, forgetting all distinction between self and world, wandering through the primal nature of things—thus will your path deepen ever more. When the Way fills your inner self, its radiance blooms upon your face, and you shall naturally return to youth's clarity, becoming one of the immortals.

    I know not whether, when you retire from office, your form shall bear the wisdom of Zhuangzi and Laozi, or whether you shall return as Anqisheng or Xianmen—those legendary sages. Yet we too shall gather, brushing our sleeves, to ask you of the Way. This is the second cause for celebration.

    Go forth, and do not surrender to excessive sorrow. Perhaps my words might offer some comfort to your heart in times of doubt. This separation spans a thousand miles—how can tears not fall? I grasp at your sleeve, wishing to hold you back, yet how can such a thing be done?
  footnotes:
    - 'Geoje (거제): An island county in the far south of the Korean peninsula, known for its isolation and harsh conditions.'
    - 'Secretariat of the Histories (봉산): The office responsible for recording official history, considered a prestigious but arduous position.'
    - 'Zhuangzi and Laozi: The legendary founders of Daoism, symbolizing spiritual attainment and transcendence.'
    - 'Anqisheng and Xianmen: Immortal figures from Chinese legend, representing those who achieved mystical enlightenment and withdrew from the mortal world.'
